Facebook Data for Good has provided us access to some data. As far as i can tell, these are the main datasets relevant to us, all west coast runs. Students, you dont have access to these pages, but were providing some of the data descriptions to you soon, and otherwise you can see this public description https://dataforgood.fb.com/tools/disease-prevention-maps/.

  • interactive movement https://www.facebook.com/geoinsights-portal/downloads/?id=545413566329986
  • colocation https://www.facebook.com/geoinsights-portal/downloads/?id=822542214917822
  • movement between tiles (most granular) https://www.facebook.com/geoinsights-portal/downloads/?id=208845507133729
  • movement between admin regions https://www.facebook.com/geoinsights-portal/downloads/?id=218786512606577
  • tile level population (probably like safegraph home panel) https://www.facebook.com/geoinsights-portal/downloads/?id=212607983438132
  • admin level population https://www.facebook.com/geoinsights-portal/downloads/?id=1112147242462205

for each of the above, ive downloaded the latest date onto the F drive. there are past dates to download eventually as well.

there is a USA run too but it looks like theyre still troubleshooting because of size.

some explanatory material here https://github.com/syjia/fbcolocation

Interactive movement

This seems to be the most granular data so Im starting here.

interactive_200409 <- 
  read_csv("F:/Restricted Data Library/Facebook/West Coast Coronavirus Disease Prevention Map Mar 11 2020 Id Id Interactive Movement Map_2020-04-09.csv") %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("start_x","start_y")) %>% 
  rename(start_geometry = geometry) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("end_x","end_y")) %>% 
  rename(end_geometry = geometry) %>% 
  st_set_crs(4326) %>% # I know this from referring to the github link above.
  separate(
    start_name_stack, into =  c("start_state","start_county"), sep = " // "
  ) %>% # only down to the city level, and there's already a separate city name field.
  separate(
    end_name_stack, into = c("end_state","end_county"), sep = " // "
  )

Note that for every pair there are 3 rows for 3 8-hr segments in a day. Below I am just summarizing all trips in a day for now.

Filter to trips starting from San Jose

bay_county_names <- # Not using this at the moment, but a reminder you can make use of a lot of GIS prep already done in other scripts if you want to filter to Bay Area.
  c(
    "Alameda",
    "Contra Costa",
    "Marin",
    "Napa",
    "San Francisco",
    "San Mateo",
    "Santa Clara",
    "Solano",
    "Sonoma"
  )

test <- 
  interactive_200409 %>% 
  filter(start_polygon_names == "San Jose") %>% 
  filter(metric_name == "n_crisis") %>% # See online documentation
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(od_pair = paste0(start_polygon_id,end_polygon_id)) %>% # This creates a unique origin-destination pair ID.
  filter(start_polygon_id != end_polygon_id) # This removes the trips that start and end in SJ because they distort the maps, but of course many analyses will want to retain this.

Line map

This view just draws straight lines from start to origin. Probably not that useful, but FB has a dashboard for researchers that does this too.

Wed have the ability to route on the real road network using osrm. This is true for Safegraph origin destinations as well.

line_map <-
  1:nrow(test) %>% 
  map_dfr(function(row){
    rbind(
      test[row,"start_geometry"] %>% st_coordinates(),
      test[row,"end_geometry"] %>% st_coordinates()
    ) %>% 
      st_linestring() %>% # These steps are just the unique way to create sf objects from scratch.
      st_sfc() %>%
      st_sf() %>% 
      as.data.frame()
  }) %>% 
  st_as_sf() %>% 
  st_set_crs(4326) %>% 
  cbind(
    end_polygon_names = test$end_polygon_names,
    metric_value = test$metric_value,
    od_pair = test$od_pair
  )

line_map_summary <-
  line_map %>% 
  group_by(od_pair) %>% 
  summarize( # This is collapsing the 3 8-hr ranges in the same day.
    end_polygon_names = first(end_polygon_names),
    metric_value = sum(metric_value, na.rm=T)
  )
  
line_map_summary %>% 
  filter(metric_value > 0) %>% 
  mapview(zcol = "metric_value")

City map

This uses tigris to plot the end destination shapes and color them, instead of the lines. Probably more useful generally.

places <- places("CA", cb=F) %>% 
  st_transform(4326) %>% 
  dplyr::select(NAME)

city_map_summary <-
  interactive_200409 %>% 
  filter(start_polygon_names == "San Jose") %>% 
  filter(metric_name == "n_crisis") %>%
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(od_pair = paste0(start_polygon_id,end_polygon_id)) %>% 
  group_by(od_pair) %>% 
  summarize(
    end_polygon_names = first(end_polygon_names),
    metric_value = sum(metric_value, na.rm=T)
  ) %>% 
  left_join(places, by = c("end_polygon_names" = "NAME")) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

city_map_summary %>% 
  filter(metric_value > 0) %>% 
  mutate( # San Jose to San Jose values removed from map because they are way bigger than any other value.
    metric_value = ifelse(
      end_polygon_names == "San Jose",
      NA,
      metric_value
    )
  ) %>% 
  mapview(zcol = "metric_value")

To do

The above scripts should be enough to let anybody start playing with the data. Some possible next steps:

  • Normalize by facebook population administrative level, which is another dataset in the F Drive. This normalization should probably be similar to the normalization of Safegraph data; refer to https://stanfordfuturebay.github.io/safegraph_patterns_normalization.html and Neels guidance.
  • Double check to see if the administrative level version is any different from lat/long. My guess is its the same but builds in the tigris style shapes instead of lat/long. It also appears you have to download those as individual 8-hr ranges.
  • Double check to see if tile data is more granular than admin data. Possibly.
  • Compare with Safegraph data. Is it showing the same general amount of movement in a given day?
  • Create some time series to show how certain kinds of movement has changed daily. Similar to Safegraph.

Questions for FB

At first glance, Im not sure this provides fundamentally different insights than Safegraph, and is less useful in the sense that it doesnt drill down to specific destination places and origin block groups. However this is based on my understand thus far, and below are some questions Id want to ask (theres a FB Slack channel to do so).

  • Is it correct that the lowest level of data granularity in the Bay Area is the admin level, and lat/long coordinates are just centroids of admin shapes?
  • What level of data omission exists? Is every individual device trip captured even if its the only device to take a specific origin-destination trip in a given time period?
  • What is the minimum movement required to be registered as moving within the same geography (San Jose to San Jose)? Or does this include no movement at all, so every device is captured?
